\end{center}

\begin{subparts}
\item The average distance of Mars from the Sun is $2.279 \times 10^8$ km.

\vgap

Write this distance as an ordinary number.

\AnswerLine[][km]
\Marks{1}

\item The planet Uranus has a diameter that is $35.8\%$ of the diameter of Jupiter.

\vgap

Calculate the diameter of Uranus.

\AnswerLine[][km]
\Marks{2}

\item The ratio diameter of Neptune : diameter of Saturn can be written in the form $1 : n$.

\vgap

Find the value of $n$.

\AnswerLine[$n = $]
\Marks{1}

\item Find the average distance of Neptune from the Sun as a percentage of the average distance of the Earth from the Sun.

\AnswerLine[][\%]
\Marks{2}

\item Distances within the solar system are also measured in astronomical units (AU).

The average distance of Jupiter from the Sun is 5.20 AU.

\vgap

Calculate the average distance of Mars from the Sun in astronomical units.

\AnswerLine[][AU]
\Marks{2}

\item The diameter of Mars is $39.2\%$ greater than the diameter of Mercury.

\vgap

Calculate the diameter of Mercury.

\AnswerLine[][km]
\Marks{2}
\end{subparts}

\item One light year is the distance that light travels in a year of 365.25 days.

The speed of light is $2.9979 \times 10^5$ kilometres per second.

\begin{subparts}
\item Show that one light year is $9.461 \times 10^{12}$ km, correct to 4 significant figures.

\Answerspace[2cm]
\Marks{2}

\item The distance from the Andromeda Galaxy to Earth is $2.40 \times 10^{19}$ km.

\vgap

Calculate the time taken for light to travel from this galaxy to Earth.

Give your answer in millions of years.

\AnswerLine[][million years]
\Marks{2}
\end{subparts}

\end{parts}

\begin{parts}
\item Lucia has two fair spinners.

Spinner $A$ is five-sided and is numbered 1, 2, 3, 4, 5.

Spinner $B$ is nine-sided and is numbered 3, 3, 3, 4, 4, 4, 4, 5, 5.

Lucia spins the two spinners and records whether they land on a prime number.

\begin{subparts}
\item Complete the tree diagram.

\relinput{Figures/Q04a-TreeDiagram.tex}

\Marks{2}

\item Find the probability that

\begin{subsubparts}
\item the two numbers are both prime,

\AnswerLine
\Marks{2}

\item the two numbers are not both prime.

\AnswerLine
\Marks{1}
\end{subsubparts}
\end{subparts}

\item Lucia spins Spinner $A$ 120 times.

\vgap

Find the expected number of times the spinner lands on a prime number.

\AnswerLine
\Marks{1}

\item Lucia spins Spinner $B$ twice.

\vgap

Find the probability that the two numbers it lands on add up to 9 or more.

\AnswerLine
\Marks{3}

